⚠️ Assumptions & Limitations

📌 Assumptions
1. Consistent Join Key (campaign_id)

It is assumed that campaign_id is available and consistent across GA4, Ads, and CRM datasets, enabling accurate joins and aggregation across sources.

2. Date-Based Incremental Logic

The pipeline assumes that all datasets contain a valid date field used for incremental processing. New data is identified using event date or ingestion date to avoid reprocessing historical data.

3. Batch File-Based Ingestion

Data ingestion is performed using a batch-based approach. Source systems export data files (CSV, JSON, AVRO) which are first stored in Google Cloud Storage (GCS) and then loaded into BigQuery raw tables using batch load jobs.

4. Append-Only Raw Data

Raw ingestion tables are assumed to be append-only. Historical records are not updated in the raw layer, and incremental logic in downstream Dataform models handles deduplication and updates.

5. Semi-Structured Data Preservation (NoSQL Layer)

GA4 and CRM datasets are stored in BigQuery using nested and repeated structures, preserving their document-style format. This acts as a NoSQL-style storage layer before transformation into relational tables.

6. CRM Data Structure (MongoDB)

CRM data is assumed to originate from a MongoDB (NoSQL) source with a semi-structured schema. Nested product arrays and return information are flattened during transformation.

7. GA4 Data Availability

GA4 data is assumed to be exported as JSON/AVRO event logs and landed in Google Cloud Storage before being batch loaded into BigQuery raw tables for transformation.

8. Data Quality at Source Level

It is assumed that source systems provide reasonably clean data, with only minor inconsistencies such as date format variations or null values.

9. Returns & Revenue Mapping

CRM data is assumed to contain sufficient fields to identify returned items and calculate net revenue accurately.

10. Time Granularity

All datasets are assumed to be aligned at a daily granularity for aggregation and reporting.

⚠️ Limitations
1. Sample Data Instead of Full Production Data

The project uses sample datasets for demonstration purposes, which may not fully represent real-world data volume, variability, or complexity.

2. No Real-Time Processing

The pipeline is batch-based and does not support real-time or streaming data ingestion. Data freshness depends on batch file availability.

3. Limited Error Handling & Logging

Error handling is implemented using SQL-based techniques such as SAFE_CAST and filtering. Advanced logging, retry logic, and monitoring are not implemented.

4. Schema Evolution Handling

Changes in source schema (especially GA4 or MongoDB) are not automatically handled and may require manual updates to transformation logic.

5. Simplified Data Quality Checks

Data validation focuses on basic checks such as null handling, deduplication, and type casting. Advanced data quality frameworks are not implemented.

6. No External Orchestration Layer

The pipeline is executed manually or through Dataform scheduling. External orchestration tools such as Airflow or Cloud Composer are not implemented.

7. Performance Optimization Scope

Basic performance optimizations such as partitioning and clustering are implemented. However, advanced optimization techniques such as materialized views and workload tuning are not included.

8. Dependency on Source Data Accuracy

The accuracy of final outputs depends on the correctness of input data from GA4, Ads, and CRM systems.

9. File-Level Deduplication Not Implemented

The ingestion layer assumes that duplicate files are not reloaded into BigQuery. Deduplication is handled in the transformation layer rather than during file ingestion.

10. Late Arriving Data Handling

The incremental logic assumes data arrives in chronological order. Late-arriving records outside the incremental window may require manual backfill.

